{
  "title": "Your First Program: <code class=\"language-python\">print()</code>",
  "description": "",
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "subtitle1",
      "text": "What is a Program in Python?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "A program in Python is simply a text file that contains instructions which the interpreter will execute line by line. The minimal structure of a program can be as simple as a single line that displays a message on the screen."
    },
    {
      "type": "note",
      "text": "üìå <strong>Note:</strong><br>In Python, each line is executed in order, from top to bottom. You don‚Äôt need a mandatory main function like in other languages."
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle1",
      "text": "The <code class=\"language-python\">print()</code> Function: Your First Tool"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The <code class=\"language-python\">print()</code> function is used to display information on the screen. It is the classic starting point in any programming language."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Basic example:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "print(\"Hello, World\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "When you run this program, Python will display:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "Hello, World"
    },
    {
      "type": "test-button",
      "text": "Try >>",
      "code": "print(\"Hello, World\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "tip",
      "text": "‚≠ê <strong>Tip:</strong><br>Everything you want to display must go inside the parentheses of <code class=\"language-python\">print()</code>. If it is text, it must be enclosed in quotation marks."
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle1",
      "text": "What Can I Display With <code class=\"language-python\">print()</code>?"
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle2",
      "text": "Text (Strings - <code class=\"language-python\">str</code>)"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "print(\"Learning Python is fun\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle2",
      "text": "Numbers"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "print(2025)"
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle2",
      "text": "Variables"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "name = \"Python\"\nprint(name)"
    },
    {
      "type": "test-button",
      "text": "Try Them All >>",
      "code": "print(\"Learning Python is fun\")\n\nprint(2025)\n\nname = \"Python\"\nprint(name)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Expected output:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "Learning Python is fun\n2025\nPython"
    },
    {
      "type": "note",
      "text": "üìå <strong>Note:</strong><br>Unlike many languages, Python does not require you to declare the variable type; simply assigning it is enough."
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle1",
      "text": "Display Multiple Values At Once"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Python allows you to print multiple elements separated by commas:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "print(\"Your age is:\", 22)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Output:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "Your age is: 22"
    },
    {
      "type": "test-button",
      "text": "Try >>",
      "code": "print(\"Your age is:\", 22)"
    },
    {
      "type": "note",
      "text": "üìå <strong>Note:</strong><br>When you use commas inside <code class=\"language-python\">print()</code>, Python automatically adds a space between each element."
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle1",
      "text": "How <code class=\"language-python\">print()</code> Works Internally"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Although <code class=\"language-python\">print()</code> seems simple, it has several useful parameters:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "print(objects, sep=\" \", end=\"\\n\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "<code class=\"language-python\">sep</code> ‚Üí Defines the separator between elements.",
        "<code class=\"language-python\">end</code> ‚Üí Defines what is printed at the end of the line."
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle2",
      "text": "Example Using <code class=\"language-python\">sep</code>:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "print(\"Python\", \"JavaScript\", \"Go\", sep=\" | \")"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Output:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "Python | JavaScript | Go"
    },
    {
      "type": "test-button",
      "text": "Try >>",
      "code": "print(\"Python\", \"JavaScript\", \"Go\", sep=\" | \")"
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle2",
      "text": "Example Using <code class=\"language-python\">end</code>:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "print(\"Hello\", end=\"...\")\nprint(\"World\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Output:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "Hello...World"
    },
    {
      "type": "test-button",
      "text": "Try >>",
      "code": "print(\"Hello\", end=\"...\")\nprint(\"World\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "note",
      "text": "üìå <strong>Note:</strong><br>By default, <code class=\"language-python\">end</code> uses <code class=\"language-python\">\n</code>, that is, a newline. That‚Äôs why each <code class=\"language-python\">print()</code> appears on a new line."
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle1",
      "text": "Spaces, Newlines, and Special Characters"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "You can control the text format using special sequences:"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "<code class=\"language-python\">\\n</code> ‚Üí Newline.",
        "<code class=\"language-python\">\\t</code> ‚Üí Tab.",
        "<code class=\"language-python\">\\\"</code> ‚Üí Quotes Within Quotes.",
        "<code class=\"language-python\">\\\\</code> ‚Üí Literal Backslash."
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Example:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "print(\"Line 1\\nLine 2\\nLine 3\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Output:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "Line 1\nLine 2\nLine 3"
    },
    {
      "type": "test-button",
      "text": "Try >>",
      "code": "print(\"Line 1\\nLine 2\\nLine 3\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "tip",
      "text": "‚≠ê <strong>Note:</strong><br>Escape sequences allow you to control exactly how the text you print looks. They are very useful for displaying menus or formatted output."
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle1",
      "text": "A Very Common Mistake When Using <code class=\"language-python\">print()</code>"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "If you forget to close the quotation marks:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "print(\"Hello)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Python will show a syntax error."
    },
    {
      "type": "test-button",
      "text": "Try Error >>",
      "code": "print(\"Hello)"
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle1",
      "text": "Minimal Structure of a Python Program"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "print(\"Hello from my first Python program\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "This is already a complete, valid, and functional program."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Output:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "Hello from my first Python program"
    },
    {
      "type": "test-button",
      "text": "Try >>",
      "code": "print(\"Hello from my first Python program\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "tip",
      "text": "‚≠ê <strong>Tip</strong><br>Think of a program as a list of instructions. If you have two lines:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "print(\"First line\")\nprint(\"Second line\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Python will always execute them in that order."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Output:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "First line\nSecond line"
    },
    {
      "type": "test-button",
      "text": "Try >>",
      "code": "print(\"First line\")\nprint(\"Second line\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle1",
      "text": "Guided Exercise: Your First Real Script"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Let's display a more personalized message."
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "name = \"YOUR NAME\"\nprint(\"Welcome,\", name, \"to the world of Python!\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Output:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "Welcome, YOUR NAME to the world of Python!"
    },
    {
      "type": "note",
      "text": "üìå <strong>Note:</strong><br>You can replace <code class=\"language-python\">\"YOUR NAME\"</code> with your own name."
    },
    {
      "type": "test-button",
      "text": "Try >>",
      "code": "name = \"YOUR NAME\"\nprint(\"Welcome,\", name, \"to the world of Python!\")"
    },
    {
      "type": "subtitle1",
      "text": "Unit Conclusions"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "In this topic you learned:"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "items": [
        "What a program in Python is.",
        "How <code class=\"language-python\">print()</code> works.",
        "How to use <code class=\"language-python\">sep</code> and <code class=\"language-python\">end</code>.",
        "How to control newlines and tabs.",
        "How to write a minimal valid program."
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "<code class=\"language-python\">print()</code> is the tool you will constantly use to see results, debug ideas, and communicate with the user."
    }
  ]
}
